Good evening.
If I could kindly\nhave your attention,
I'm delighted to\nintroduce and welcome
Alison Brooks, who's\nteaching at option studio
here this semester.
This year marks the\n22nd anniversary
of Alison Brooks's practice,\nwhich Alison opened
after seven years as partnered\nwith Ron Arad Associates,
where she worked on projects\nsuch as the foyer of the Tel
Aviv Opera House.
If often think if we\nmeasured years as distance
in one's career, I\nthink 20-odd years
would be considered\nto be long distance
in many other professions\nor disciplines.
But it's not often the\ncase in architecture.
We think about Le Corbusier's\n60 year career, or Frank Lloyd
Wright's 70 year career,\nbut in many ways,
I think Alison's\ntrajectory is one
that belongs to this\nlong distance mentality.
As opposed to the ones\nwhose career accelerated
at the outset, I\nthink Alison belongs
to a secular sector, a\ngroup of perennial outsiders
who are on the slow burn.
This group-- they're very good.
They're very serious\nabout the work.
They're not on the fast\ntrack, but pursuing
their own architectural\ninterests with a tenacity,
with quirkiness and confidence,\nand producing quietly
subversive work.
While many of us-- so some\nof us have been following
her work for a long time.
I think many outside\nof architecture--
the architectural\ncognoscenti might not
be aware of Alison's work\nuntil the debut of the pavilion
called the Smile, designed for\nthe London Design Festival.
And those of you who've been\nto London in recent years,
even if you have not noticed\nthe distinguished vertical forms
throughout the\ncity, a taxi driver
could tell you which one\nis the Gherkin, which
one is the Shard, which one\nis the Walkie Talkie, which
one is the Cheese Grater,\nwhich one is the Can of Ham.
You can practically\nhave a picnic.
So I think in 2006 it was\nvery refreshing to experience
a more horizontal, a more\nephemeral model named
the Smile.
The project itself is an\naccomplishment from a design,
from a structural, and\nmaterial standpoint.
Alison Brooks was born\nin Ontario, Canada.
She moved to London after\nstudying architecture
at Waterloo, and over the many\nyears she won many awards.
She is the only UK\npractice to have
won RIBA's three most\nprestigious architecture
prizes.
That includes the Stirling\nPrize, the Mensa medal,
and the Stephen Lawrence Prize.
Alison herself was\nawarded the AJ Woman
Architect of the Year in 2013.
And after many years\nof honing her craft,
Alison's practice is booming.
Her work now encompasses\nurban design, housing,
education buildings, and\nbuildings for the arts.
Although many of the projects\nare designed very distinctive
for very specific\ncases and sites,
I think one could\ntrace her [inaudible]
throughout her work.
There's always a strong\ncommitment to the public realm.
There's a vast\nknowledge and commitment
to the history of\nurban typology,
as one could see the use and\ntransformation of type such as
[? mies, ?] or quads,\nor arcades in her work.
Her work often bridges between\nthe Victorian or Georgian
historical fabric of London,\nand the brutalist work
from the 1960s.
She really understands her\nwork as a process of healing
or stitching this urban fabric.
I think on the surface--
I think Alison is a\nmodernist architect.
There's clearly a sensitivity to\nmaterials, context, and scale,
but I think behind\nthat type of politeness
there's a strong\nrigor and insistence.
Those of you who\nmight have heard her--
heard her say things like she\ninsists on designing nothing
under 2.6 meters for\na room height, which
is like eight and a half feet.
Or there's nothing better\nthan a French door,
so why reinvent it?
But what I love about\nthis dichotomy--
this dichotomy that she has\nbetween restraint and rigor
is very different\nfrom those [inaudible]
kind of strict\ndivision between, let's
say, a reserved\ngentlemanly facade
for this Georgian exterior with\na hedonistic luxurious interior
hidden within the inside.
Her work kind of\ndeals with these two
opposites by oscillating\nconstantly between the two,
so it's always an act in motion.
And to end my\nintroduction, I'd like
to quote one of our\ndistinguished alumnus, John
[? hader. ?] He said there's\na short distance runner
architect, and there's a long\ndistance runner architect.
The short distance runner is\njust that-- a short distance
runner.
The short distance runner's\ntrail is straight, flat,
and the end can be seen.
The short distance runner\nis a crowd pleaser.
The short distance runner runs\nfast and is soon out of breath.
The long distance runner's\nscope is simply vaster.
The long distance runner\ntraverses a more complex
landscape.
The long distance runner\ngets better with age.
The long distance runner's\ndistance is extended.
The long distance runner's\narchitecture at once
because sparser and richer.
So I hope after this\nlecture it leaves no doubt
that Alison Brooks has\nsigned on as a long distance
runner traversing through the\nlong and treacherous terrain
demanded of every architect.
So please join me\nin welcoming Alison.
