And one of the\nvery first projects
I had when I started my\npractice was the VXO House,
and I like to show\nthis image because it
was a 1960s house of a client\nwho'd had a fire in the house.
And she called me\nup, and I knew her
from when I worked\nwith Ron Arad.
And she said, could you\ndesign me a new shelf?
And that was the\nshelf that she--
for her office that she\nwanted a new design for.
And it turned into\nthis project, which
is the VXO House, which was a\ncomplete renovation, extension
of the house.
So everything was gutted--
an extension to the front,\nadditional bedroom and foyer,
and then a gym and\nguest house here
where there was a garage\nbefore, and a carport over here.
And this project, in a\nway, launched my practice,
because, well, it's got an RIB\naward, and it was published.
And I treated this\nproject as I treat
all of my domestic projects,\nas a kind of essay,
a testing of ideas.
And in a way, this was my\npurest modernist experiment,
where I wanted to sort\nof really emphasize
the kind of '60s quality\nof the house with sort
of floating volumes and\nvery graphic structure.
Every element--\neven the front door
is a sort of object unto itself.
There is a huge\nwall that's actually
a wall drawing by\nSimon Patterson,
and you walk through a door\nin the wall to the cloakroom.
It's made of sort of\nautonomous pieces,
and each one is expressed\nas an individual thing.
And the idea was to\ncreate a kind of campus.
So it's like a domestic campus--
the house, which is the V,\nand then the X pavilion,
which is supported\nwith a sort of X
shaped structure replicating\nthe shape of a human body,
and then the O port, which is\na sort of impossible structure.
The load comes down via an\nO shaped piece of steel.
So it was a kind of\nlighthearted project,
but very serious\nat the same time.
I made the retaining\nwalls out of pebbles
to evoke sort of grottoes.
The roof was held off the walls\nso that it reads as a tray--
suspended staircase\nthat acts as a screen.
So each object had\nits own kind of role.
But after that\nproject, I felt I'd
kind of exhausted\nthat sort of essay,
and it was time to\ntry something new.
And this was a house extension\nin South London, where I sort
of took the opposite approach.
I wanted to make the whole\nextension out of one element.
And so this is the one element,\na three mil thick sheet
of brass.
And so by a series\nof cuts and folds,
the single sheet creates\ncolumns, sunshades, benches,
facades, roof, internal\nwalls finishes.
So this was, in a way,\ntrying to reduce architecture
to its absolute minimum--
just one piece, one element--
and to make it\nkind of disappear.
So I started working with\nmirror polished stainless steel
