So at the other end of the\nspectrum, around the same time,
I was doing competitions\nfor housing and regeneration
projects in London.
So this is Northwest London.
This is this area called\nSouth Kilburn, which
is just north of Notting Hill\nfor any of you who know London.
But I like to show\nthis image because it
shows how London was in 1938.
It was a kind of expression\nof a complete and perfect
Victorian city.
The Victorians were\namazing urban designers.
They don't really get\ntalked about very much,
but this neighborhood\nhad huge parks.
This is Paddington\nrecreation ground.
This is all mansion\nblocks and [inaudible]
terraced houses, avenues.
Kilburn Park Road, all sort of\nshops lining the major streets,
sort of interesting chevron\nshaped arrangements,
and triangular squares\nwith churches and terraces.
I mean, it was a kind of\ncomplete neighborhood.
And it was completely raised.
This was the sort of master plan\nfor this part of South Kilburn
in 1952, I think it was.
And so the idea was to destroy--
demolish all of the terrace\nhouses, and all of the streets,
and basically sprinkle slab\nblocks around in green space.
And actually, most of this\nwas built, but at the time,
a sort of local\nresidents association
decided to fight back, and\nthey prevented all of this
from happening.
And this is a\nconservationary, although this
was built, as well.
So the kind of amazing misguided\napproach to re-urbanization
still leaves its mark not only\nin London, but many cities all
over the world.
And this is actually an image\nof this part of the master plan
right here.
So this was supposed\nto be the town center,
and everything is boarded up.
The streets were\nall blocked off,
and this was supposed to be a\nsort of plaza for residents,
and there are these\nslab blocks replacing
what were terraced streets.
And I participated in a\ncompetition in, I think, 2010
to actually--
the local authority,\nBrent Council--
they sponsored-- most\nLondon municipalities
sponsor competitions\nand regeneration master
plans for their estates.
They're called failed states--\nbasically, your sink estates,
and which are generally\nsocial housing.
They're not a mixed community.
They're kind of low\nincome communities,
and there are a lot\nof problems in them
due to not only sort of\nsocial and income segregation,
but architectural segregation\nand kind of failed urban design
principles.
So you can see here how the\nsort of slab blocks that
were in that sort of 1952\nmaster plan are still here,
and then there's\nsort of green space
and then funny sort\nof low rise blocks.
And in a way, it looks\nfine because you think,
oh, there's all this green\nspace, and it's all kind of OK,
but this was a really, really\ndangerous neighborhood here.
And this I've just shown as\na kind of cultural divide
between the have nots\nand the haves who
occupy the sort of\nhistoric typologies.
And so this project\nfor Ely Court,
which I'm going to talk about up\nhere, is one of three projects
that I've worked on\nin South Kilburn.
All of them were competitions.
All of them were collaborating\nwith other architects.
So Lifschutz Davidson\ndid this piece up here,
and I did this piece, and then\nwe shared again on this site.
And then with Feilden\nClegg Bradley on that site.
And the local authorities\nreally appreciate that.
They don't want one\narchitect doing everything.
They don't want to repeat\nthe mistakes of the past
where you have a\nsort of monoculture--
architectural monoculture.
So my approach here was to--
in a way, very\nstraightforward-- to restore
the frontage to the street\nwith a terrace block here,
which is actually\na mansion block.
So these are duplexes\nwith entrances every three
flats and a little apartment\nbuilding down here,
another apartment,\nmews houses, and then
a piece here that\nsort of completes what
we call the flat iron block.
And the idea of this--
well, all of these-- was to\nkind of re-frame this piece
of neglected space to create\na public garden square where
all of the buildings around sort\nof have a role in overseeing
and sort of reactivating this\npiece of neglected space.
And this was formerly just a\nplace that you would never go,
because if you didn't live there\nin one of these slab blocks,
you would never go in there.
So the idea of introducing\na new street that
connects through to\nthe rest of the block
brings people going to\nschool, all sorts of movement,
and cars and traffic, which\nare good at a slow speed.
And these are the typologies--\nthe mansion block,
the flat iron, and\nthe mews block.
And so in a way, when\nyou see our project here,
it feels like it's\nnot very radical.
It's just kind of framing the\nspace of the street in the way
that the historic\nbuildings have always done,
but actually this is\nwhat these sites need.
They need a kind\nof normalization.
They need a direct relationship\nto the street with front doors,
with lots of windows, and\na kind of very clearly
defined public space.
And so, in a way,\nthe opportunity
