And in the book, I sort\nof describe my work
according to these themes,\nthese sort of techniques,
or tactics, or themes that\nactually have influenced
most of-- well, all of my work.
But I I've actually decided to\ntalk about this word models,
and name this talk Model\nBuilding because I think
the word models is, in a way,\nmore instrumental than the word
ideals.
I'm really interested\nin language
and the way we articulate\narchitectural ideas with words,
and we use the word model\na lot, but we use it
very loosely and in\nmany different ways
that I think a lot of\npeople don't relate
to outside of the profession.
And so how do we combine this\nidea of ideals and models?
What does it mean?
And of course there's one way\nof using the word models, which
is building models, typological\nmodels, theoretical models,
conceptual,\ninstitutional, and urban.
And we all sort of know\nwhat we mean by those--
that they're sort of exemplar,\nand they're sort of ideal.
But in the other way, we can\nexpress the word model even
in a way emphasizing\nthat quality that applies
not only to objects such\nas houses, but also people.
So model family, model\ncommunity, model organization.
And in a way, this idea\nof model society I think
is what we're in a way--
the expectation\nis that someday we
will achieve a model society,\nbut what is that model society,
and how does architecture\ncontribute to that
and allow many different kinds\nof models and model scenarios
to exist and to co-exist.
So this idea of\nmodel building I felt
was really important to\ndiscuss and sort of articulate.
In the context of my\nproject in Oxford,
which was a competition I\nwon in 2011 for the new Cohen
Quad in Oxford--
and this is a kind\nof model community.
Oxford colleges-- I am not sure\nif they're exactly the same
here at Harvard, but\nOxford is made up
of colleges, which are\nactual communities.
They are autonomous,\nindependent communities,
and not only is Oxford--
its sort of pedagogical\nmodel based on colleges,
but it's architectural\nmodel and morphology
is based on colleges,\nwhich are quadrangles.
And so each one of these\nquads represents a college,
and that college is a community\nmade of fellows, and students,
and staff, who live, and\nteach, and learn in the quad.
And this model comes from\nthe monastic tradition.
They were started\nas monasteries that
then became secular and now\nform the kind of college model
that we all know and love.
And so when I was shortlisted\nfor this competition, of course
I did a lot of research\ninto the history of Exeter
College, its quads, and the\namazing kind of roof line
and amalgamation of\ndifferent periods
and styles of\narchitecture, but framing
a collective space and the\nvery thin buildings that
were accessed by stairs--
one stair per sort of community,\nin a way serving two rooms.
And Exeter College is\nthis bit right here.
So it's an amazing 700 year\nold campus with beautiful
Neo-Gothic chapel and gardens--
fellows gardens,\nfront quad, back quad.
And then all of these\nare other colleges--
Jesus College, John's College,\nTrinity College, et cetera.
And this typology always is\nabout framing a space, a sort
of collective outdoor space.
And the nature of Exeter College\nand Turl Street is very much
about these framing spaces,\nbut then jewel buildings--
this incredible jewel\nbuilding, which is 1865--
George Gilbert\nScott-- basically one
of the most beautiful examples\nof Neo-Gothic architecture
in the UK.
And this kind of\nlegacy is something
that you have to sort\nof take on board when
you work for an Oxford college.
So when we won the\ncompetition, the idea
was that it would be\nfinished for their 700 year
anniversary, which was in 2014,\nwhich was going to be difficult
since that was 2011.
So we only had four years,\nand this is the site up here
in the top left hand corner.
So basically all of the land\nin Central Oxford is gone.
It's taken, and this\none site came up,
which was the site of a\nformer Ruskin College.
And all of the colleges\nwere bidding for it,
but Exeter College got\nit, which was very lucky.
And we were given\na project brief,
and really the project\nbrief was to reinvent
the collegiate ideal\nfor the 21st century.
That was the kind of\nsummary statement.
And you can see it includes\nmany, many different kinds
